December 18, 2015

Fast and Clean

Do stuff faster (and cleaner?) with dplyr

Do stuff cleaner (and faster?) with broom

dplyr

Function Action
select() Select colums
filter() Filter rows
mutate() Add columns
summarise() Summarize columns
group_by() Perform grouped operations
left_join() SQL-like join operations

broom

Function Action
tidy() Summarize model findings (like summary())
glance() Concise one-row model summary
augment() Add columns to modeled data (like predict())

Other Packages (used today)

  • Lahman
  • ggplot2
  • magrittr

The Pipe

The Pipe Operator

The Basics:

  • x %>% f is the same as f(x)
  • x %>% f(y, .) is the same as f(y, x)

A Data Question

Can you name the baseball players with 4 letters or fewer in their last names who have hit 40 or more home runs in a season? (source: Sporcle)

Knowing Your Data (with Mark McGwire)

Batting %>% 
  filter(playerID == "mcgwima01") %>% 
  select(playerID, teamID, yearID, HR) %>% 
  filter(yearID == 1997)
##    playerID teamID yearID HR
## 1 mcgwima01    OAK   1997 34
## 2 mcgwima01    SLN   1997 24

Knowing Your Data (with Mark McGwire)

Batting %>% 
  filter(playerID == "mcgwima01") %>% 
  group_by(playerID, yearID) %>% 
  summarise(HR = sum(HR)) %>% 
  filter(yearID == 1997)
## Source: local data frame [1 x 3]
## Groups: playerID [1]
## 
##    playerID yearID    HR
##       (chr)  (int) (int)
## 1 mcgwima01   1997    58

Home Run Data

hr <- Batting %>% 
  group_by(playerID, yearID) %>% 
  summarise(HR = sum(HR)) %>%  
  ungroup %>% 
  filter(HR >= 40) %>% 
  group_by(playerID) %>% 
  summarise(seasons = n(),
            last_year = max(yearID)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(seasons))

Player Name Data

players <- Master %>% 
  tbl_df %>% 
  select(playerID, nameFirst, nameLast) %>% 
  mutate(letters_last = nchar(nameLast))

The Solution

hr %>% 
  left_join(players, by = "playerID")  %>% 
  filter(letters_last <= 4)

Another Data Question

What is the relationship between a baseball team's yearly player salaries and the team's winning percentage?

Team Salaries vs. Win Percentage

Salaries (in millions)

money <- Salaries %>% 
  group_by(yearID, teamID) %>% 
  summarise(total_salary = sum(salary) / 1000000)

Team Salaries vs. Win Percentage

Winning percentage

wins <- Teams %>% 
  tbl_df %>% 
  filter(yearID >= 1985) %>% 
  mutate(win_pct = W / (W + L) * 100) %>% 
  select(yearID, teamID, win_pct, LgWin, WSWin) %>% 
  left_join(money, by = c("yearID", "teamID"))
## Source: local data frame [858 x 6]

Summarize the (2014) Model

The model

m1 <- lm(win_pct ~ total_salary, data = filter(wins, yearID == 2014))
m1

Test ALL the Model Slopes

Without broom

sapply(split(wins, wins$yearID), function(x) {
  mm <- lm(win_pct ~ total_salary, data = x)
  summary(mm)$coefficients["total_salary", "Pr(>|t|)"]
})
